Facts (layer 2):

`show` (VariableExpression):
  has bound(s) `Describe` `Number` (resolved as `instance (Describe Number)`)
  has type `Number Number Number -> ()` or `Number -> ()`
  is an expression
  resolved to 1 definition(s): `show :: value -> () where (Describe value)`

`show 1 2 3` (ExpressionStatement):
  has type `()`

`show 1 2 3` (CallExpression):
  has type `()`
  is an expression

`1` (NumberExpression):
  has type `Number`
  is an expression
  type is annotated

`2` (NumberExpression):
  has type `Number`
  is an expression
  type is annotated

`3` (NumberExpression):
  has type `Number`
  is an expression
  type is annotated



Feedback:

`show` (conflicting-types)

  `show` is a `Number Number Number -> ()` or a `Number -> ()`, but it can only be one of these.
  
  `show` must be the same type as `1`, `show 1 2 3`, `2`, and 1 other; double-check these.

  1. `show`: `show` displays `1` on the screen.

  2. `1`: `1` is a `Number`.

  3. `2`: `2` is a `Number`.

  4. `3`: `3` is a `Number`.

  (1 -> error, 2 -> 1)
